@component ws-core
@intent deps-0 raw WebSocket (RFC 6455) transport core for the Constellation live board. Sits below `server.cjs` — handles HTTP upgrade, SHA1+GUID handshake, frame parse/write, masking removal, heartbeat ping/pong, optional token validation, and the `WSConn` connection object. The server implements higher-level policy (HELLO/relay/broadcast) on top. Pure transport — no application semantics: msgId, Ack/AckProcessed, dedup watermark are application-layer concerns belonging to bridge + agent per §13.13 layer split (server/bridge/agent), and this module neither generates nor inspects them. **v0.2 fragmented assembly**: opcode 0x0 continuation frames ARE handled — a start frame (0x1 text or 0x2 binary) with FIN=0 begins accumulation in `_frag`, subsequent 0x0 frames append, and FIN=1 closes the sequence via `Buffer.concat → _deliver`. Single-frame path (FIN=1 on start) remains the fast path. TCP chunk accumulation across `data` events is independently handled via `buf`. Real driver for v0.2: browser-side WS clients fragment large attachments (e.g. data-URL images) and the v0.1 single-frame-only codec silently dropped them — a real downstream-adoption defect where image attachments never reached the board. (Distilled from `constellation/reference/runtime/ws-core.cjs` at v2.3.x — drift fix from v2.2.x reference ship per main delegate seq 23/25; fragmented assembly added per main delegate seq 35 / production fb9f876.)
@expansion temperature=0.2 model=agent/claude template=estreux/v0.0.1
@targets runtime
@state
# Module-level
_seq         : number = 0           # outbound event sequence counter (event() monotonic across process)
GUID         : string = const       # RFC 6455 magic '258EAFA5-E914-47DA-95CA-C5AB0DC85B11'
# Per-connection (WSConn instance)
socket       : net.Socket           # underlying TCP socket
buf          : Buffer = empty       # TCP chunk accumulator (across `data` events)
alive        : boolean = true       # connection liveness
id           : string               # 6-byte hex (randomBytes) — connection id
meta         : object = {}          # server fills after HELLO (agentId, role, collab/upstream flags)
onmessage    : (msgObj) => void     # server-installed text-frame handler
onclose      : () => void           # server-installed close hook
devAuth      : boolean              # true when token env unset (dev mode no-auth)
_frag        : object|null = null   # fragmented frame chunk accumulator { chunks: [Buffer, ...] }; null in single-frame mode (set on FIN=0 start frame, reset to null after final FIN=1 concat)
_hb          : Timer                # 20s ping interval handle
@ports
in   req        : http.IncomingMessage   # HTTP request with upgrade headers + url + sec-websocket-key
in   socket     : net.Socket             # raw TCP socket from `upgrade` event
in   LIVE_BOARD_WS_TOKEN : string?       # env optional auth token (alias WS_TOKEN); unset = dev no-auth
in   query.token : string?               # `?token=...` query-string token (alternative to Bearer)
in   header.authorization : string?      # `Authorization: Bearer <token>` (alternative to query)
cmd  handleUpgrade(req, socket) → WSConn|null   : validate upgrade headers + sec-websocket-key + token → write `HTTP/1.1 101 Switching Protocols` + `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` → new WSConn; null on auth fail (401 written before destroy) or missing upgrade/key (socket.destroy without 4xx)
cmd  event(type, fields) → object               : envelope builder `{type, id:'evt_'+hex5, seq:++_seq, timestamp:Date.now(), source:'server', ...fields}` — canonical for all server→client wire messages
cmd  getToken() → string                        : read env `LIVE_BOARD_WS_TOKEN || WS_TOKEN`; '' on dev mode
cmd  acceptKey(key) → string                    : SHA1(key+GUID)base64 — RFC 6455 §1.3 handshake response
cmd  encodeFrame(payload, opcode) → Buffer      : unmasked server frame (FIN=1; len <126 inline / 126+u16BE / 127+u64BE)
cmd  decodeFrame(buf) → {fin,opcode,payload,totalLen}|null : parse single frame from accumulator; null when payload not yet complete (caller retries on next chunk)
out  conn.send(objOrString) → boolean           : JSON.stringify if object → text frame 0x1; false if !alive or socket write throws
out  conn.close()                               : send close frame 0x8 + socket.end + _dead (idempotent)
out  conn.onmessage(msgObj)                     : server-installed handler invoked per text-frame JSON.parse success
out  conn.onclose()                             : server-installed handler invoked once at _dead
out  conn.remoteAddr : string                   : `socket.remoteAddress` with `::ffff:` IPv4-mapped-IPv6 prefix stripped — the server reads it for HELLO-origin logging (anonymous-probe defense, see server.eux register(HELLO))
out  conn.ua : string                           : request `User-Agent` header (`''` if absent) — same HELLO-origin observability path as `remoteAddr`
deps crypto                                     : node:crypto (sha1 hash + randomBytes); non-Node targets (Bun / Deno / Workerd) substitute equivalents
deps net.Socket                                 : raw TCP from node http upgrade; non-Node targets substitute equivalent stream w/ `on('data')` + `write()` + `end()` semantics
@behavior
handleUpgrade : require `Upgrade: websocket` header (else socket.destroy + return null); require `Sec-WebSocket-Key` (else same); parse `new URL(req.url, 'http://localhost')` for query token; validateAuth via env token + (`?token=` OR `Authorization: Bearer <token>`) either match passes; empty env = dev mode `{ok:true, dev:true}`; on auth fail write `HTTP/1.1 401 Unauthorized\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n` + destroy + null; on success write 101-handshake response with `Sec-WebSocket-Accept: <acceptKey(key)>`; new WSConn(socket); set `conn.devAuth = auth.dev`; expose `conn.remoteAddr = (socket.remoteAddress || '').replace(/^::ffff:/, '')` (strip IPv4-mapped IPv6 prefix so server logs render plain IPv4 when applicable) + `conn.ua = req.headers['user-agent'] || ''` (origin observability for the server's anonymous-probe path); return WSConn.
WSConn.constructor : wire `socket.on('data', _recv)` + `socket.on('close', _dead)` + `socket.on('error', _dead)`; `setInterval(_hb)` every 20000ms sending empty ping (opcode 0x9); init `buf=empty`, `alive=true`, `id=randomBytes(6).hex`, `meta={}`.
WSConn._recv(chunk) : `buf = Buffer.concat([buf, chunk])`; loop `decodeFrame(buf)` until null — slice off `totalLen` from buf; opcode dispatch: `0x8` close → `this.close()` and return; `0x9` ping → reply pong (opcode 0xA, same payload), continue; `0xA` pong → ignore; `0x1` text OR `0x2` binary (start frame) → if `fin` call `_deliver(payload)` immediately (single-frame fast path), else `_frag = { chunks: [payload] }` (fragmented start); `0x0` continuation AND `_frag` set → push payload to `_frag.chunks`; on `fin`, `Buffer.concat(_frag.chunks) → _deliver(full)` and reset `_frag = null`. Continuation without `_frag` is silently dropped (malformed sequence — no error throw to keep the connection alive).
WSConn._deliver(payload) : single entry point for both single-frame and fragmented-assembled paths — `JSON.parse(payload utf8)`; on parse error return silently (single bad message doesn't kill connection); on success call `this.onmessage(msg)` if set.
WSConn.send : if object, `JSON.stringify`; else use string; `_frame(Buffer.from(s,'utf8'), 0x1)`.
WSConn._frame : if `!alive` return false; try `socket.write(encodeFrame(payload, opcode))` return true; on throw return false (silent drop — caller handles via send return value).
WSConn.close : if `!alive` return; try `socket.write(encodeFrame(empty, 0x8))` + `socket.end()`; `_dead`.
WSConn._dead : once-only guard (`if (!alive) return`); set `alive=false`; `clearInterval(_hb)`; call `onclose()` if set.
event : `Object.assign({type, id:'evt_'+crypto.randomBytes(5).toString('hex'), seq:++_seq, timestamp:Date.now(), source:'server'}, fields||{})`. Module-level `_seq` is monotonic for this process; resets only on server restart.
acceptKey : `crypto.createHash('sha1').update(key + GUID).digest('base64')`.
decodeFrame : RFC 6455 §5 parse — `fin = (buf[0] & 0x80) !== 0` (FIN bit; used by `_recv` for fragmented vs single-frame branch); `opcode = buf[0] & 0x0f`; `masked = (buf[1] & 0x80) !== 0`; `len = buf[1] & 0x7f`, `off = 2`; if `len === 126` read `u16BE` at offset 2 (need ≥4); if `len === 127` read `u64BE` at offset 2 (need ≥10, convert via `Number(BigInt)`); if masked, read 4-byte mask key (need extra 4); if `buf.length < off + len` return null (payload not yet complete); `payload = buf.slice(off, off + len)`; if masked, XOR `payload[i] ^ mask[i % 4]`; return `{fin, opcode, payload, totalLen: off + len}`.
encodeFrame : `header[0] = 0x80 | opcode` (FIN bit always set); `len < 126` → `header[1] = len` (2-byte header); `len < 65536` → `header[1] = 126` + `u16BE` at offset 2 (4-byte header); else → `header[1] = 127` + `u64BE` at offset 2 (10-byte header); `Buffer.concat([header, payload])`.
@machine
# WSConn liveness state
states: ALIVE(initial) · DEAD
dispatch:
  TCP_CLOSE       : ALIVE → DEAD   (entry: clearInterval _hb; call onclose() if set)
  TCP_ERROR       : ALIVE → DEAD   (same — error treated as close, transport-level recovery is caller's responsibility)
  CLOSE_FRAME_IN  : ALIVE → DEAD   (entry: write close 0x8 then _dead)
  CLOSE_EXPLICIT  : ALIVE → DEAD   (caller invokes conn.close() — same as CLOSE_FRAME_IN)
derive:
  send_gate ← `_frame` returns false when `!alive` (silent drop, no throw — caller checks return value)
  hb_lifecycle ← `_hb` interval starts in constructor, cleared in `_dead` (no leak after close)
  fragmented_supported ← opcode 0x0 cross-frame continuation IS handled (v0.2) — start frame (0x1 text or 0x2 binary) with FIN=0 begins accumulation in `_frag = { chunks: [] }`; subsequent 0x0 continuation frames push payloads; FIN=1 closes the sequence via `Buffer.concat(chunks) → _deliver(full)`. Single-frame path preserved as fast path (FIN=1 on start delivers immediately without touching `_frag`). Malformed continuation (0x0 without `_frag` set) is silently dropped — no throw, connection stays alive. TCP chunk accumulation via `buf` is orthogonal and also handled (large single-frame messages reassemble across `data` events).
  application_layer_orthogonal ← msgId / Ack / AckProcessed / dedup watermark (§13.13) live in bridge + agent layers; ws-core is pure transport and neither generates nor inspects them. Hooks deferred to first production §13.13 PR per main delegate seq 23 (transport-application separation preserves §13.13 layer split).
  envelope_canonicalness ← server-side application messages MUST use `event('CUSTOM', {name, value})` per server.eux @intent envelope convention; bare top-level types (SERVER_HELLO / HELLO / Heartbeat / PersistentAdapterSmoke) are reserved for transport framing only. Mixing produces silent drops on strict-envelope dashboards — that pitfall is the convention's reason for existing.
